{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bdd24640-158d-4e3b-b3a2-fc96cde03541","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| `--auth` Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Example:**\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --name MyApi\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need a custom identity provider. Would you like me to scaffold a project with a specific auth option?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"48e1550a-450f-47c1-9fa9-12cbe784bdf4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context mentions dotnet). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"33CE:D1352:1DB299C:217C275:69E81964"},"id":"86a69358-d2c2-4766-b21f-69fdf899e13d","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:42:19.719Z","parentId":"8d079bd3-0d3b-4e58-ae66-24ea98ed1770"}
